# Project Libraries

This directory contains project-specific PlatformIO libraries. Each library owns
one clear part of the ESP32 firmware so the project does not grow back into a
single legacy-style monolith.

## Display

`Display` is the hardware-facing graphics service:

- initializes LovyanGFX;
- configures the SPI TFT panel;
- configures backlight PWM;
- configures XPT2046 touch;
- exposes controlled access to the LovyanGFX device;
- protects display/touch bus access with a mutex.

`graphic_screens` is the UI rendering and routing layer:

- owns day/night palette selection;
- renders boot, main, options placeholder, overlays, and small update regions;
- owns the current screen route and main soft-button page;
- converts touch coordinates into high-level `UiAction` values;
- keeps service calls out of drawing functions.

Implementation rule: drawing helpers draw only. Application effects such as
STOP, tracking, WiFi, SD, or OTA must be handled by services outside rendering.

## Input

`Input` owns local touch sampling:

- the XPT2046 IRQ only wakes the task;
- SPI touch reads happen outside the ISR;
- press/release events are debounced;
- events are queued for the display/UI layer.

This keeps interrupt work short and avoids mixing input sampling with screen
routing.

## Mount

`Mount` owns the ESP32-to-STM32 boundary:

- `ModbusMaster` setup;
- RS485 driver-enable control;
- command queue;
- STM32 status/position polling;
- mount state snapshot;
- high-level APIs for GOTO, STOP, tracking, motors, and jog.

The module publishes intent to STM32. It does not implement motor physics and
does not generate pulses.

STOP is treated as a priority command and must stay independent from tracking
enable/disable.

## Telescope

`Telescope` contains shared telescope state and LX200 formatting:

- controller logical clock;
- site coordinates;
- current object name;
- current RA/DEC representation;
- LX200 date/time/coordinate string helpers;
- firmware identity and configuration access through `config.h`.

This module should remain a state/model helper. Hardware IO belongs in service
modules.

## System

`System` contains small board-level services:

- slow system inputs such as night mode;
- optional CPU load monitor;
- optional FreeRTOS task/heap diagnostics.

These features should stay optional and low priority.

## PlanetCalc

`planetcalc.h` is a header-only astronomy helper for future local object and
planet calculations. It should remain independent from display, Modbus, WiFi,
and storage so it can be tested on host builds.
